    "body": "These are all supposed use cases. Presently, Crypto Kitties has not identified a need for searching historical kitty names, Crypto Kitties users have not expressed a similar need, people do not use Ethereum for blogs, newspapers have not talked about Ethereum being used for blogs. Usually the actual use cases come first, then competing implementations happen, and then when everybody has made their mistakes, then a standard emerges.\r\n\r\n# Philosophy aside, now for technical discussion\r\n\r\n* This would require a list of all contracts to search. Contracts to hyperlink to others so you would need to search the web to find them.\r\n* Implementing search on even one contract would require an unfathomable amount of gas.\r\n* Implementing search on even one contract would require recording history forever (e.g. immutable data structures everywhere) even EVM does not have this much storage.\r\n* Implementing search on even one contract would require a significant number of lookup tables and it would only ever work on full word queries. \r\n\r\n# Alternate solution\r\n\r\nA website makes a list of many known contracts and allows you to search them. It uses contract-specific code to search each contract using the full history of that contract (and all logs).\r\n\r\nAfter the alternate exists in the wild, that might be the time to start talking about a search standard.",
